      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. what actually is escrow and why can't i just pay the seller directly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, a concept that's quite familiar to the Canadian real estate market, is a trust account that holds funds for a specific purpose, in this case, paying off outstanding debts or taxes associated with the property. It's a bit like a temporary storage facility for your money, where it's kept safe until the transaction is complete. You can think of it as a secure, escrowed box that holds the funds until the agreed-upon conditions are met.\n\nNow, you might wonder why you can't just pay the seller directly. Well, escrow serves as a safeguard to ensure that all parties fulfill their obligations. For instance, if the seller has outstanding mortgage payments or property taxes, the escrow account will hold funds to cover these expenses. This way, you can be sure that the seller's obligations are taken care of, and you're not left with any unexpected surprises.\n\nIn Toronto, where the real estate market can be quite competitive, escrow is a common practice to prevent disputes or misunderstandings. It's a bit like a mutually agreed-upon insurance policy, where both parties are protected in case something goes awry. So, while it may seem like an added layer of complexity, escrow is actually a crucial aspect of",
      "source": "target",
